\begin_layout BeginFrame
Non homogeneous Bernoulli Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the components are nonhomegeneous w.r.t.
 the corresponding reliabilities, then the calculation is a bit more complicated
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{k\mid n} & = & 1-\sum_{\mid I\mid>=k}\left(\prod_{i\in I}(1-R_{i})\right)\left(\prod_{i\notin I}R_{i}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 ranges over all choises 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}<i_{2}<\dots<i_{m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq m\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the reliability of th 
\begin_inset Formula $i-$
\end_inset

th component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider a non homogeneous TMR with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{2\mid3} & = & 1-(1-R_{1})(1-R_{2})R_{3}-(1-R_{1})(1-R_{3})R_{2}+\\
 &  & -(1-R_{2})(1-R_{3})R_{1}-(1-R_{1})(1-R_{2})(1-R_{3})\\
 & = & R_{1}R_{2}+R_{2}R_{3}+R_{1}R_{3}-2R_{1}R_{2}R_{3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

