\begin_layout Definitions

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\noindent
A random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that its CDF 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function is called a continous random variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dx$
\end_inset

 exists everywhere (except perhaps for a finite number of points) is called
 an absolutely continuous random variable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Definitions

\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The continuous uniform random variable having CDF 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(x)=\begin{cases}
\begin{array}{r}
0,\\
x,\\
1,
\end{array} & \begin{array}{l}
x\leq0\\
0<x<1\\
x\leq1
\end{array}\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

is absolutely continuous having a derivative at all point except at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Continuous random variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Probability Density Function).
 For an absolutely continuous random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=dF(x)/dx$
\end_inset

 is called the probability density function (pdf or density function) of
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pdf enables us to obtain the CDF and hence to compute probabilities
 by integrating the pdf, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{X}(x)=P(X\leq x)=\int_{-\infty}^{x}f_{X}(t)dt\mbox{ for }-\infty<x<\infty\mbox{ and}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(X\in(a,b]) & = & P(a<X\leq b)\\
 & = & P(X\leq b)-P(X\leq a)\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{b}f_{X}(t)dt-\int_{-\infty}^{a}f_{X}(t)dt\\
 & = & \int_{a}^{b}f_{X}(t)dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Continuous random variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pdf satisfies the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)dx=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CDF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of a continuous random variable satisfies the following properties 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq F(x)\leq1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<x<\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 is a monotone increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\to-\infty}F(x)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\to\infty}F(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CDF of a continuous random variable does not have any jumps, therefore
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(X=c)=\int_{c}^{c}f_{X}(t)dt=0.
\]

\end_inset

This does not imply that the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X=c\}$
\end_inset

 is empty, but that the probability assigned to it is 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Continuous random variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The time in years, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, required to complete a software project has a pdf of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{X}(x)=\begin{cases}
\begin{array}{l}
kx(1-x),\\
0,
\end{array} & \begin{array}{l}
0\leq x\leq1\\
\mbox{otherwise}
\end{array}\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy property 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Because of property 2 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{0}^{1}kx(1-x)dx & = & k\left(\frac{x^{2}}{2}-\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right)\mid_{0}^{1}=1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 from which we deduce 
\begin_inset Formula $k=6.$
\end_inset

 The probability that the project will be completed by less than four months
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(X<\frac{4}{12} & =F_{X}(\frac{1}{3}) & =\int_{0}^{1/3}f_{X}(x)dx=\frac{7}{27}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

or about 25 percent chance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout EndFrame

\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Mixed random variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes the involved random variable will either be descrete or continuous,
 but a mixed random variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
There may be a nonzero probability, say 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0},$
\end_inset

 of initial failure of a component at time 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 due to manufacturing defects.
 In this case the time to failure 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of the component is neither discrete nor a continuous random variable!
 Assuming an exponential distribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $CDF$
\end_inset

 will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{X}(x)=\begin{cases}
\begin{array}{l}
0,\\
p_{0},\\
p_{0}+(1-p_{0})(1-e^{-\lambda x}),
\end{array} & \begin{array}{c}
x<0,\\
x=0,\\
x>0.
\end{array}\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, a mixed random variable will have a 
\begin_inset Formula $CDF$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{X}(x)=\alpha_{d}F^{(d)}(x)+(1-\alpha_{d})F^{(c)}(x)
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{(d)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{(c)}$
\end_inset

 are two discrete and continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $CDF$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

