\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
Weibull Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Weibull distribuiton is the most widely used parametric family of failure
 distributions.
 It has been used to describe 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
fatigue failure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
electronic component failure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ballbearing failure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason is that by a proper choice of the shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 we can obtain an IFR, DFR or constant failure rate distribution.
 The corresponding density and distribution functions are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f(t) & = & \lambda\alpha t^{\alpha-1}\exp(-\lambda t^{\alpha})\\
F(t) & = & 1-\exp(-\lambda t^{\alpha})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

